Limitations notwithstanding, the MD-simulated trend agree largely with experiment. Predicted LLPS propensities quantified by the Tcrs in Fig. 6 follow the rank order of WT > 4Rto4KM > 4RtoKN ≈ 4Rto4KC > 15Rto15K, which is essentially identical to that measured experimentally, viz., WT > 4Rto4KM > 4RtoKC > 4Rto4KN > 15Rto15K (Fig. 9B of ref. [73]). In comparing theoretical and experimental LLPS, a low theoretical Tcr can practically mean no experimental LLPS when the theoretical Tcr is below the freezing temperature of the real system [16, 109]. Fig. 6a shows that even the highest Tcr for 15Rto15K (at model [NaCl] = 480 mM) is essentially at the same level as 

Tcr0

 for WT at [NaCl] = 0 (

Tcr/Tcr0≈1

). This MD prediction is consistent with the combined experimental observations of no LLPS for 15Rto15K up to at least [NaCl] = 2 M and no LLPS for WT Caprin1 at [NaCl] = 0 (Fig. 9B,C of ref. [73]).
